"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:3.1.4\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">3.1.4</span> Window</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">אֲרֻבָּה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(’arubah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen7:11\">GEN 7:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen8:2\">GEN 8:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs7:2\">2KI 7:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs7:19\">2KI 7:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Eccl12:3\">ECC 12:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa24:18\">ISA 24:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa60:8\">ISA 60:8</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hos13:3\">HOS 13:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mal3:10\">MAL 3:10</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">חַלּוֹן</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(chalon)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen8:6\">GEN 8:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen26:8\">GEN 26:8</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Josh2:15\">JOS 2:15</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Josh2:18\">JOS 2:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Josh2:21\">JOS 2:21</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Aramaic</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">כַּוָּה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(kawah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan6:11\">DAN 6:11</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">צֹהַר</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(tsohar)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen6:16\">GEN 6:16</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">שֶׁקֶף, שְׁקֻפִים</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(sheqef, shqufim)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs6:4\">1KI 6:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs7:4\">1KI 7:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs7:5\">1KI 7:5</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">θυρίς</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(thuris)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts20:9\">ACT 20:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor11:33\">2CO 11:33</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Tob3:11\">TOB 3:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir14:23\">SIR 14:23</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Macc3:19\">2MA 3:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/INVALID\">DAG 6:11</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/OAI-0031_windows_en.jpg\" alt=\"\n            \"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">\n             (Image generated by ChatGPT using OpenAI technology)</figcaption></figure>The window was an opening in a wall for the entrance of light and air and for the purpose of seeing in or out.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>In some languages a distinction is made between windows that may be closed with glass or shutters and those that are simply openings. It is probably the latter type that is involved in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hos13:3\">HOS 13:3</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts20:9\">ACT 20:9</a>; and <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor11:33\">2CO 11:33</a>, while it is clear that <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen6:16\">GEN 6:16</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen8:6\">GEN 8:6</a>; and <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan6:10\">DAN 6:10</a> speak of the former type. Generally, translators should avoid a word for “window” which indicates something made of glass, which was not used in windows in the ancient world.</p>\n<p>The Hebrew word <em>’arubah</em> occurs in the phrases “windows of heaven” (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen7:11\">GEN 7:11</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen8:2\">GEN 8:2</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa24:18\">ISA 24:18</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mal3:10\">MAL 3:10</a>) and “windows in heaven” (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs7:2\">2KI 7:2</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs7:19\">2KI 7:19</a>). It is not necessary to translate these phrases literally, as seen in <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr>, which renders the first phrase as “floodgates of the sky” in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen7:11\">GEN 7:11</a> and <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen8:2\">GEN 8:2</a> and “Torrents of rain … from the sky” in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa24:18\">ISA 24:18</a>. For the literal expression “if the LORD himself should make windows in heaven” in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs7:2\">2KI 7:2</a>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> has “even if the LORD himself were to send grain” (<a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs7:2\">2KI 7:2</a>).</p>\n<p>Opinions differ concerning the meaning of <em>’arubah</em> in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Eccl12:3\">ECC 12:3</a>. Some versions (for example, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Spanish Common Language Version (Dios Habla Hoy)\">SPCL</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Traduction Oecuménique de la Bible (French, 1975)\">TOB</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr>) translate literally “those [women] who look through windows,” while others take it to be a reference to the eyes (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr> “your eyesight”; <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Century Version\">NCV</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"German Common Language Version (Gute Nachricht Bibel)\">GECL</abbr> “your eyes”).</p>\n<p>The Hebrew phrase <em>chalone shqufim ’atumim</em> in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs6:4\">1KI 6:4</a> is understood in various ways. Some translations find technical words for a particular architectural feature; for example, for the whole verse <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised English Bible (1989)\">REB</abbr> has “and he fitted the house with embrasures,” and <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr> says “He made narrow clerestory windows in the temple.” Both of these examples demonstrate what should not be done in a common-language translation, using words that may be technically correct but are obscure to the reader. They would have achieved approximately the same effect by transliterating the Hebrew. Some understand these windows to be covered with a kind of “lattice,” “grill,” or “grate” (compare <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Spanish Common Language Version (Dios Habla Hoy)\">SPCL</abbr>). Others interpret the phrase as describing the structure of the window in the wall; for example, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> says “The walls of the Temple had openings in them, narrower on the outside than on the inside,” and <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr> has “The windows were narrow on the outside but wide on the inside.” Some think that a kind of “frame” for the window is being described: “And he made for the house windows with recessed frames” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr>). <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Jerusalem Bible (1985)\">NJB</abbr> combines two of these elements into “He made windows for the Temple with frames and latticework.” When choosing a translation here, it should be kept in mind that the probable purpose of these openings was to allow light into an otherwise rather dim Temple interior. Many translations add a footnote saying that the Hebrew is unclear.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
